<body>

    <header>
        <h1>Informative Speech Outline</h1>
        <h2>From Land to Sea - How Recycling in Colorado Impacts Ocean Health</h2>
    </header>

    <section class="introduction">
        <h3>Introduction</h3>
        <p><strong>Attention Grabber:</strong> Every year, more than 8 million tons of plastic waste enter our oceans. Many would assume that plastic only comes from coastline cities, but did you know that a significant amount of this waste comes from places far away from the coast, even places like Colorado? Now if you thought 8 million was bad, that figure was made by a 2015 study published in Science by Jambeck.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Ethos Establisher:</strong> As someone who’s deeply concerned with our planet’s future and the growing issue of excessive waste, I’ve spent time researching how recycling – even in landlocked areas like ours – really does make a difference in our fight for environmental purity.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Thesis and Listener Link:</strong> Yes, I will admit that Colorado is far from the nearest oceans, however, our recycling and waste management efforts are more connected to the health of the oceans and the overall environment than we truly realize.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Preview:</strong> Today, we will explore:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>The benefits of recycling</li>
            <li>How plastic reaches our oceans</li>
            <li>The damage it causes to marine life</li>
            <li>Innovative uses for recycled plastics</li>
            <li>What we can do here to contribute</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="body">
        <h3>Body</h3>

        <h4>First Main Point: The benefits of recycling</h4>
        <p><strong>Subpoint:</strong> To put it simply, recycling reduces the need for raw materials, like petroleum used to make plastics. Globally, we produce over 300 million tons of plastic annually, and according to the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), recycling just one ton of plastic can save up to 5,774 kWh of energy.</p>

        <p><strong>Subpoint:</strong> Recycling also reduces the amount of waste that ends up in landfills, which is not just for conserving space, but also helps reduce methane emissions and groundwater contamination.</p>

        <p><strong>Transition Statement:</strong> Now, these are some good benefits, but what happens when waste is not properly managed? Where does it go?</p>

        <h4>Second Main Point: How plastic reaches our oceans</h4>
        <p><strong>Subpoint:</strong> Many are surprised to learn that plastic waste from land-locked areas like our home in Colorado can end up in the ocean. Rivers, wind, and poor waste management can carry plastics for thousands of miles, eventually reaching coastal waters. A 2017 study in Nature Communications by Lebreton explains in detail how rivers are just like conveyor belts for plastic debris.</p>

        <p><strong>Subpoint:</strong> The Colorado River, for example, is part of a larger network of waterways that connects to the Pacific Ocean. The U.S. Geological Survey notes that pollutants can travel vast distances through river systems, contaminating not only the rivers themselves but also the oceans they feed into.</p>

        <p><strong>Transition Statement:</strong> Once in the ocean, this plastic is very harmful, especially for marine life.</p>

        <h4>Third Main Point: The damage it causes to marine life</h4>
        <p><strong>Subpoint:</strong> Plastic waste in the ocean has a devastating effect on marine animals. The most known creatures affected by this are sea turtles, who often mistake plastic bags for jellyfish, one of their primary food sources, leading to fatal blockages in their digestive systems. Seals such as the Hawaiian monk seal and Cape Fur Seal, for example, get tangled in all sorts of debris, leading to injury or death.</p>

        <p><strong>Subpoint:</strong> Microplastics and nanoplastics, tiny particles of degraded plastic, were first found in marine life but are now detected in nearly all ecosystems, even in humans. These extremely small plastics not only affect the health of these animals but also raise concerns about our well-being and long-term health.</p>

        <p><strong>Transition Statement:</strong> However, it is not all bad news. Through new solutions, we still have a little time to turn this problem around.</p>

        <h4>Fourth Main Point: Innovative uses for recycled plastics</h4>
        <p><strong>Subpoint:</strong> Many companies are finding new and creative ways to use recycled plastics. For example, the outdoor brand Patagonia creates jackets from recycled plastic bottles, while companies like Adidas have created sneakers using ocean plastic waste.</p>

        <p><strong>Subpoint:</strong> Researchers are also developing new methods to use recycled plastics in construction, such as creating plastic bricks that are stronger and more durable than traditional materials.</p>

        <p><strong>Transition:</strong> These are all great achievements, but innovation isn't enough… What can we do, right here in Colorado, to make a difference?</p>

        <h4>Fifth Main Point: What we can do here to contribute</h4>
        <p><strong>Subpoint:</strong> In Colorado, there are multiple recycling programs in place that support global sustainability efforts. The state's Extended Producer Responsibility (EPR) pushes for manufacturers to take responsibility for the waste their products create.</p>

        <p><strong>Subpoint:</strong> On an individual level, Coloradans can help by reducing single-use plastics or participating in clean-up programs.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="conclusion">
        <h3>Conclusion</h3>

        <p><strong>Summary Statement:</strong> To sum everything up, recycling is necessary in preserving our world, whether it’s preventing waste from reaching our rivers and lakes or creating new sustainable products from reused materials.</p>

        <p><strong>Clincher:</strong> Together, by making conscious decisions to recycle and reduce waste, we can help protect not just the world’s oceans but also our environment here in Colorado.</p>
    </section>

</body>
